# NOTE: Keep this list short (~8 entries). Remove old ones as new ones land.
CHANGELOG = [
    "b435: Bonepicker Reaver joins the strong-monster art pass -- the 52nd key now renders a gaunt six-armed, blade-fisted reaver from the strong-monsters atlas (cell s09_03) in place of its old round-8 sprite. Same pipeline as b434: pid MN2535's pool image + its sprite_picks/monsters overlay overwritten with the 96x96 webp, and _MONSTERS_MAP collapsed to the single chosen variant.",
    "b434: fresh art pass for the top of the bestiary -- all 51 strong-monster keys (the 11 bosses/legendaries plus the 40 shard-guardian & deep-tier elites) now render hand-picked sprites from the new Gemini strong-monsters atlas instead of the old round-8 picks. Each key was matched to one sprite via a custom in-browser picker; the chosen cells are tight-framed to ~68% and encoded the pool's way (96x96 RGBA webp q80), patched into canonical_pool_full.pkl, and mirrored as sprite_picks/monsters overlays so a future promote_all_sprites rebuild keeps them. _MONSTERS_MAP was repointed key-by-key (reusing each key's existing primary pid, so no orphans) and collapsed to the single chosen variant. ZOT'S GUARDIAN -- previously special-cased with no sprite -- gets its first dedicated entry (new pid MN5000).",
    "b433: monsters now LOOK like they're casting, not just say so in the log. Until now a Beholder's disintegration ray and a plain bite both rendered as a shaken panel + a number -- all the spell flavor lived only in the combat log. Now every one of the 33 caster monsters gets a cast SIGNATURE that reuses the player's own FX pipeline: a spell-name banner + full-screen element tint + element particle burst, scaled by the monster's level (a F15 Nightmare Lich's Death Bolt flashes at max intensity; a F2 Cockatrice gaze is a subtle flicker), plus a phone buzz on the big casts and on every petrify gaze. Element is picked per spell (Necrotic->Darkness, Mind Blast/Disintegration->Psionic, Heat Metal->Fire, Petrify->Earth, heals->green, shields->gold); particles burst from the player panel for attacks and the monster's own panel for self-buffs/heals. A casting monster stashes a small descriptor on gs.last_monster_spell_cast; the renderer builds a lightweight Spell-shim from it and feeds the existing generate_spell_cast_js / generate_spell_particles_js (now with a delay arg so the flourish lands in the monster's turn window, ~1.9s in, not on top of the player's own banner). Wired into both the partial-update and full-render paths.",
    "b432: monsters can now TELEPORT, in two flavors. BANISH (Sphinx, Rakshasa, Illithid Overmind) warps the floor around you and flings you to a random empty tile far from the fight -- the monster stays put with its current HP, so you have to trudge back across the floor to finish what you started. BLINK (Wraith, Rimebound Djinn) is an escape hatch for a wounded caster: it heals itself and vanishes to another spot on the floor, leaving you standing on empty stone to hunt it down (it'll only bolt ~60% of the time when hurt, and prefers a real heal over fleeing if it has one, so it isn't an un-killable kite). The fiddly part is that teleporting has to end the current fight and move entities mid-combat without corrupting the view; the spell only sets a flag during the monster's turn, and combat.resolve_pending_monster_teleport() does the actual relocation + clean exit (mirroring the flee path) once the combat handler has fully returned -- wired in at the app loop right after the two combat handlers, so every monster-turn path is covered. Also fixes a petrification fairness spike from b431: gazes now carry a 1-turn cooldown (a general per-spell cooldown mechanic), so a Medusa/Basilisk can no longer chain-petrify on back-to-back turns and delete a full-HP character before they get to act -- you're now guaranteed a turn between every stage. 33 monsters now cast.",
    "b431: three new monster-spell mechanics that make build choices matter, because the same fight should scare a tank and a mage differently. MANA BURN (Mind Flayer, Illithid Overmind, Elder Brain, Demilich) devours your mana and deals psychic backlash scaling on what it drained -- it shreds a spell-reliant build but a pure-melee character with an empty pool just shrugs. HEAT METAL (Efreeti, Cinderborn Efreet, Infernal Warlord, Fire Giant, Balrog) deals fire damage that SCALES WITH YOUR ARMOR -- the better-armored you are, the more it cooks you, so a heavy-plate tank suddenly fears the smith-giant. Both route through take_damage (which doesn't subtract defense) so the scaling lands clean. And PETRIFICATION SAVE-OR-DIE: the gaze monsters (Medusa, Basilisk x2, Gorgon x2, Cockatrice) now actually turn you to stone -- each gaze adds a stage, and reaching the per-monster threshold (3 for the deadly ones, a forgiving 4 for the low-level Cockatrice) kills you outright. It's fair: stages 1..N-1 are loud escalating warnings, and if you kill the gazer or flee, the petrification simply recedes as the effect expires -- no cure item required. 32 monsters now cast.",
    "b430: the spellcasting roster goes wide + the casters get a real toolkit. b429's playtest showed the spell engine barely surfaced -- only the base Lich cast, and it's rare, so the deep liches you actually fight (Dragon Lich, Hollow/Necrarch/Sepulchral/Nightmare Lich) just swung. Now 24 monsters across every tier carry spell lists: all the liches (necrotic bolts + self-heals), the psionic line (Mind Flayer/Illithid Overmind/Elder Brain mind-blast + a Dominate stun), the genies & fiends (Efreeti/Djinn/Warlord/Demilich/Night Hag/Succubus elemental bolts, drains, and heals). Two new spell mechanics back the marquee casters: self_buff spells (a monster wards ITSELF -- Monster.take_damage now honors hit_absorb, so a Lich's Force Shield eats a couple of blows) and spell_ward (a Rakshasa's Spell Turning counters your NEXT spell -- checked in Character.cast_spell). The Beholder is the showpiece: a five-ray menu (Disintegration / Antimagic-silence / Petrification-stun / Slowing / Enervation) picked at random each turn, so no two rounds look alike. Deep bolts bypass armor but sit well under the monster's brutal melee, so they read as variety, not a difficulty spike.",
    "b429: caster monsters now actually CAST SPELLS. Until now even the bestiary's wizards just swung melee with an on-hit status rider -- a Lich named for being an undead archmage hit you with a stick. New monster-spellcasting layer: a caster carries a 'spells' list + a per-turn 'spell_chance', and Monster._try_cast_spell() (called at the top of attack_target) may cast a spell INSTEAD of swinging -- alternative damage, not bonus. Three spell types: damage (routes through take_damage so it BYPASSES armor like the player's own spells, but still respects elemental resistance / Stone Skin / Spectral Hand), heal (the monster mends itself, preferred when below 50% HP), and debuff (applies a status via the existing effect machinery). First wave of casters: Lich (Necrotic Bolt + a Drain Vitality self-heal), Sphinx (Word of Power), Rakshasa (Mind Twist + a Phantom Veil that blinds you), and the bug-level Firefly Mage (Lumen Lance) + Dragonfly Enchantress (Prismatic Bolt + an enervating weakness charm). Spells pass through at both the normal and bug-monster spawn sites; non-casters are unaffected. The roster is data-driven, so widening it to the deep liches/fiends later is just more 'spells' entries.",
    "b428: monsters fight like the monsters they're supposed to be. A huge swath of the bestiary had special_attack entries that were pure flavor -- the log bragged about a Lich's necromantic blast or a Kraken's crushing coils, but mechanically NOTHING happened, because the effect types weakness/slow/curse (and a 'drain' typo on the Dragon Lich) were never wired into combat. Now they bite: weakness saps the player's effective attack by its magnitude (Character.attack), curse/defense_penalty pry your guard open by reducing defense (Character.defense), slow gives a 30% chance each turn that your sluggish action fizzles while the monster strikes freely, and Dragon Lich's drain is now real life_drain. That alone turns ~30 cosmetic specials into genuine threats (Lich, Beholder, Rakshasa, Mummy, Tarrasque, Basilisk, Kraken, the deep liches, ...). Both attack/defense clamp at >=0. Also: monster passive regeneration (new 'regen' template field, fraction of max HP/turn) -- the Troll now knits its wounds each turn (burn it down or stalemate). And ~11 formerly-vanilla bruisers got thematic specials: Owlbear/Griffin/Bulette bleed, Minotaur/Roc/Cyclops gore-stun, Hill Giants daze (weakness), Stone Golem slam (slow), Frost Giant freeze, Crawling Claw clinging grip (sticky_hands), Displacer Beasts blur your aim (blindness). Pure low-tier fodder (goblins, kobolds, orcs, gnolls, bats) stays honest melee.",
]

